{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"370"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/370"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.06,0.49,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102001"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/370"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"370"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84451"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-month-old boy is brought by his mother to the General Practice clinic after an episode of what she suspected is gastroenteritis. The boy has loose bowel actions for four days, and his mother noticed blood in the stool. This is associated with severe episodic crying after feeds and an asymptomatic period between the crying spells. His four-year-old sister recently had similar symptoms and her symptoms resolved within two days. His mother took his temperature, which was 38.1\u00b0C yesterday, and it is now checked and is normal. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stool culture","Full blood examination","Ultrasound of the abdomen","Blood culture","Abdominal X-ray"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child with bloody stools after what seems like viral gastroenteritis is consistent with the diagnosis of intussusception. Whilst vomiting is a common associated symptom in children with intussusception, it is not always present. The patient had exposure to his older sister who presented with symptoms of viral gastroenteritis. Viral infections stimulate the lymphatic tissue that leads to hypertrophy of Peyer\u0027s patches in the intestines, which may act as a lead point for intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntussusception is most commonly seen between 6 and 18months. In the majority of cases, it is idiopathic with no known lead point. However, a few cases may have evidence of a lead point. The common lead points include Meckel\u0027s diverticulum, viral gastroenteritis-induced hypertrophy of Peyer\u0027s patches, Henoch-Schonlein purpura, or tumours. The ileocolic junction is most commonly involved; however, ileoileal intussusception may also be seen in Henoch-Schonlein purpura. Patients typically present with episodic abdominal pain with drawing up of the legs and bloody stools. While there is a lack of signs (e.g., abdominal mass, indrawing of the knee) in this patient, this does not exclude the diagnosis. The presence of bloody stool after viral gastroenteritis is highly suggestive of intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination may show a sausage-shaped mass in the abdomen and right upper and lower quadrant tenderness. \u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most sensitive (\u0026gt;98%) and specific (\u0026gt;98%) test for the diagnosis of intussusception. It would reveal the intussuscepted segment of the intestines within the lumen (also known as the target sign).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Estool culture\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated in patients with persistent diarrhoea (due to gastroenteritis), immunosuppression, or in an outbreak. It is rarely required for viral gastroenteritis but may be performed in patients with persistent bloody stools to rule out bacterial causes. It is generally not the initial test. Furthermore, cyclical crying spells (possibly due to abdominal pain) are more consistent with the diagnosis of intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood examination\u003C/strong\u003E may be performed to check for anaemia (due to bloody stools) and leucocytosis (due to gastroenteritis). However, it will not be the most appropriate test in diagnosing the cause of his pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are not required for viral gastroenteritis nor intussusception. They may be performed in patients who present with persistent fever or sepsis. This patient is afebrile at this moment and does not demonstrate signs or symptoms of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E are not sensitive (\u0026lt;50%) or specific enough to diagnose intussusception. They may aid the diagnosis of intussusception by excluding other possible conditions. An AXR may be required if there are signs of obstruction or perforation which would then require urgent surgical review. However, abdominal ultrasound remains the best initial investigative test for intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal ultrasound should be the initial investigation in a case of suspected intussusception."],"references":["Bartocci M, Fabrizi G, Valente I, Manzoni C, Speca S, Bonomo L. Intussusception in childhood: role of sonography on diagnosis and treatment. J Ultrasound. 2014 Jul 19;18(3):205-11. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4529406/","Henderson AA, Anupindi SA, Servaes S, Markowitz RI, Aronson PL, McLoughlin RJ, Mistry RD. Comparison of 2-view abdominal radiographs with ultrasound in children with suspected intussusception. Pediatr Emerg Care. 2013 Feb;29(2):145-50.  Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23364378/","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. ntussusception. Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/intussusception/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84451"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"370"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84451"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T10:54:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T10:55:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"370"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102001"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},